xander</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Prichard</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH015507%2F1"><gtr:id>9BC8364F-0A54-4A84-BECC-A49DF466DA63</gtr:id><gtr:title>Justice, Order and Anarchy: The International Political Theory of Pierre-Joseph Proudhon (1809-1865)</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H015507/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>While Thucydides, Hobbes, Kant, Grotius and even Marx are the most well-known intellectual ancestors of the discipline of International Relations, other more prolific and at their time more influential writers have been all but forgotten. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>One such figure is the first nineteenth-century anarchist, Pierre-Joseph Proudhon (1809-1865). He wrote nearly 2000 pages on European international relations that have been completely ignored by contemporary IR scholars. Proudhon's writings in this area were well-known and influential at the time. Indeed, Tolstoy decided to entitle his magnum opus after Proudhon's two-volume work &lt;em>La Guerre et la Paix. Recherches sur la principe et la constitution du droit des gens [War and Peace: Investigations into the principle and constitution of the rights of nations] (1861).&lt;/em>&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Alex Prichard's doctoral research sought to contextualise this text intellectually, socially and geo-politically. The aim was to demonstrate how it fit into Proudhon's wider anarchist political philosophy, how Proudhon engaged with key debates in French and European political culture, and whether it advanced those debates.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The primary aim of the postdoctoral fellowship is to disseminate this research by publishing four articles, drawn from the thesis, in key IR journals and to redraft the thesis for publication with a prestigious university press. &lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>79424</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>I have been able to show that the anarchist Pierre-Joseph Proudhon gives us a radically new approach to the concept of anarchy in IR. I aligned his thought with the republican ideal of non-domination, arguing that anarchy, rather than statism, is the most appropriate institutional form for realising non-domination. Over the course of a number of publications, I show that Proudhon is an unjustifiably ignored figure in the history of international and political thought.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Constitutional theorists and institutional design might benefit from my research</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>2A258A2B-15E9-40E5-8F41-07177678584D</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>546b46bc5554c9.87630283</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>52AF9551-29F1-40DF-8BFB-1BDE